# Overview 

The purpose of this solution is to provide general [Power Automate](https://powerautomate.microsoft.com/en-ca/?cdn=disable) flows for actions that I have needed to use frequently. 

## Who is this for?
This solution includes flows that require a premium PowerAutomate account:
- 🛠️ Format Date
- 🛠️ Save Email as PDF

Moreover, all the Excel and OneDrive actions require a business account, so if you use a personal account, you cannot use any flows with a OneDrive or Excel connection (without modifying them and replacing the business actions with general ones). The following flows use OneDrive or Excel actions:
- 🛠️ Copy file as a PDF
- 🛠️ Ensure Valid Excel Table
- 🛠️ Get Excel Table Columns
- 🛠️ Get Prop Names
- 🛠️ Save Email as PDF

## Editing the Flows
If you use this solution, please note that editing the flows anywhere will cause it to be updated in ALL instances in the Environment. If you want to make minor changes in a flow without modifying its use throughout the environment, you can edit it and click **Save As** to create a new copy. You can edit the new copy instead of modifying the original. Of course, you can edit the original flow directly but use caution and take note of all of its uses to not destroy any existing functionality. 

## Connectors Used
We use the following Connectors:
- [OneDrive](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/connectors/onedriveforbusiness/)
- [Excel](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/connectors/excelonlinebusiness/)
- [Outlook](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/connectors/office365/)
- [RegEx Matching](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/connectors/regexmatchingip/)

We use many expressions in the flows:
- [List of Expression Functions](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/logic-apps/workflow-definition-language-functions-reference)
- [Introduction to Expressions](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/training/modules/introduction-expressions/)


# Getting Started
## Initial Setup
1. Download the solution ZIP file: [Utilities_1_0_0_1.zip](https://github.com/ArianaAvdoulosEPL/Power-Automate-Utility-Flows/blob/main/Utilities_1_0_0_1.zip)
2. Download the Excel scripts. 
3. Import the solution into your Power Automate environment. For help importing solutions, see: [Import a solution](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/power-automate/import-flow-solution)
4. Set connection references. 
- The **🔌 🛠️  Excel: PowerAutomate Admin Utility** and **🔌 🛠️  OneDrive: PowerAutomate Admin Utility** *MUST* be connected to the same account. 
- The **🔌 🛠️ Excel Script Connection** should be saved to an account that can access the Excel scripts. 
5. Edit the flow **🛠️ 🌳 ENVIRONMENT** and update the variables to match your Environment

## Using Flows
These flows can only be used independently or as child flows of other flows in the Dataverse. See [Call Child Flows](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/power-automate/create-child-flows) to learn about Child Flows. If the flow doesn't run as a child flow, then check that the flow is **NOT** set to **provide run-only users**. To do this:
1. Go to the flow details page
2. Under **Run only users** click **Edit**
3. The flow connections will be listed with a dropdown to change the connector. Ensure that no connectors are set to **provide run-only users**

When using a utility flow as a child flow in a new solution, adding that flow to the new solution is good practice. When adding a utility flow to a new solution, you must add *ALL* of its dependencies. See the [Dependency Tree](https://github.com/ArianaAvdoulosEPL/Power-Automate-Utility-Flows/wiki/Dependency-Tree) page to determine a flow's dependencies.

## Common Import Problem
Even with all the steps above completed, sometimes Power Automate provides an error because it cannot identify the library used. To fix this issue, you must go into the flows and manually select a library for each Excel and OneDrive action. The following flows use OneDrive or Excel actions:
- 🛠️ Copy file as a PDF
- 🛠️ Ensure Valid Excel Table
- 🛠️ Get Excel Table Columns
- 🛠️ Get Prop Names
- 🛠️ Save Email as PDF

# Conventions
These are a list of conventions used in creating the flows and a brief explanation of why it is done.

# Ⅰ. Define Trigger Inputs as Trigger Variables.

![Define Trigger Inputs as Trigger Variables Example](./README_pics/Define_Trigger%20Inputs_as_Trigger_Variables.png)

Power Automate references trigger inputs by their index, although you can give a name. For example, in the above photo, *File Content* is at index 0, and the *File Name* is at index 2. Suppose you delete some inputs or change their order in any way. Any references to the inputs in expressions will have to update. Needing to update references is only a concern when referencing trigger inputs in expressions rather than variables. As such, it is best to have an intermediate step where you attribute the trigger input directly to a variable. To be concise, when defining variables whose value comes from the trigger, *Trigger:* is always prepended to the variable name.

# Ⅱ. Add a Note Describing the Intended use of a Variable on Initialization

![Add a Note Describing the Intended use of a Variable on Initialization Example](./README_pics/Add_a_Note_Describing_the_Intended_use_of_a_Variable_on_Initialization.png)

Adding a note at the initialization allows any maintainers (including yourself, in case you forget) to understand the purpose of a variable immediately without needing to analyze the flow to ascertain its meaning.

# Ⅲ. Add all Expressions to a Note.

![Add all Expressions to a Note Example](./README_pics/Add_all_Expressions_to_a_Note.png)

Power Automate hides the arguments of an expression, only showing the expression identifier. For instance, you can only see *or* in the expression above. Furthermore, when expanded, the input box for the expression is small, so the expression's end usually gets cut off. In the photo above, you can see that the end of the expression is cut off in the text box. By putting the expression in the note, anyone can see the contents of the expression without expanding it and simply glancing at it.

# Ⅳ. Define Actions at a High-Level Using Scopes and Then Drill Down to More Specific Actions.

![Define Actions at a High-Level Using Scopes and Then Drill Down to More Specific Actions Example](./README_pics//Define_Actions_at_a_High_Level_Using_Scopes_GOOD.png)

Starting at a high-level abstraction and drilling down allows maintainers to quickly understand the function of the flow and each step of it by glancing over it. Compare the above photo with the one below. The image below is the same flow but without the scopes used. The one above should seem significantly more straightforward. Furthermore, it is helpful for you as you are developing the code. This way, you can quickly outline the process and fill in the logic later. 

![Example of Not using Scopes](./README_pics//Define_Actions_at_a_High_Level_Using_Scopes_BAD.png)

# Ⅴ. Change the Action Name to Better Describe It but Do Not Remove the Default Action Name

![Change the Action Name to Better Describe It but Do Not Remove the Default Action Name Example](./README_pics/Do_Not_Remove_the_Default_Name_GOOD.png)

Actions can be identified using their names. When instantiated into the flow, the Action has its name as a default name. Users can rename the Action however they wish, but I implore you **not**
 to remove the default Action name. Including the default name in the Action lets the maintainer know precisely what each Action is performed. The photo above shows that "Create a share link by path" is being used. Below, you can still understand what Action is being performed, but it would need to be clear what base action was used.

![Removing the Default Name](./README_pics/Do_Not_Remove_the_Default_Name_BAD.png)

As you may notice from the image above, I have used the convention:

```
Default Name: Specific descriptor
```

# Ⅵ. Avoid Using the Compose Action

![Compose](./README_pics//Avoid_Using_the_Compose_Action.png)

The Compose action should only be used for comments, as a data preview, or as a placeholder. The value of the Compose action is tied to its name, so if you change the name of the Compose for any reason (ex: better fitting name, incorrect spelling), then you must also change every instance using the former name to the new name. Use variables instead. 

# Ⅶ. Handle Exceptions in the Flow

![Handle Exceptions in the Flow Example](./README_pics//Handle_Exceptions_in_the_Flow.png)

The parent flow will timeout when there is an error in a child flow. This makes it difficult to ascertain the source of the error and slows the entire flow. To handle exceptions, create *terminations*/*Return to PowerApps* actions that run on error instead of allowing the flow to error.

# Ⅷ. Use Version Control Software to Maintain Flows

Power Automate solutions can be downloaded and uploaded to version control software. For this project, I have used GitHub. Version control software easily allows users to return to previous versions if needed for any reason.

# Ⅸ. Use Labels to Group Items Together

Each Utility flow is prefixed by 🛠️ and all Connection References are prefixed by 🔌 🛠️. The 🛠️ symbol is the solution label, and the 🔌 sign indicates the item is a Connection Reference. Power Automate groups items by alphabetical order; as such, all objects sharing the same label appear together in a list. This groups utility flows and connection references together. Moreover, when adding an item to a different solution, you can tell what solution the item was originally from by its label. For this reason, I also recommend adding the label as a prefix to the solution's display name. 

# Ⅻ. Define Connection References for Each Solution

While the **🛠️ Utilities** solution includes connection references for Excel and OneDrive, I would advise against using them in other flows solutions. These connection references encapsulate the utility flows to a single connection location; you could also change the location of utility operations by changing these few connection references. Suppose you use these connections in other solutions and want to change them in one solution. In that case, it is time-consuming as you need to create another connection for that solution and replace each instance. Creating dedicated connections for solutions allows you to avoid this mishap. I also caution against using a different connection reference for each flow; fewer connections will enable you to manage them more easily. Moreover, most operations done in a solution take place in a single connection environment. In essence, create different connection references for each flow, but do not create more connection references than needed in a solution. 

# ⅫⅠ. Include a Definition on Each Flow

At the start of each flow, I include a Compose action named **📢 DEFINITION** that explains the flow:
- Purpose
- Inputs
- Outputs
- Dependancies

# Connection References

**The connections for OneDrive and Excel *MUST* use the same Microsoft account.**

These are the connections used in this solution. The latter three connections can be used across different solutions as they are general connectors. It may be wise not to use the first two connectors across different solutions as they preform specific and more intensive file operations in this solution. 

## 🔌 🛠️  Excel: PowerAutomate Admin Utility
Used to access Excel tables and rows from Excel files in the connected Mircosoft account's OneDrive. 

## 🔌 🛠️  OneDrive: PowerAutomate Admin Utility
Used to access files and folders in the connected Microsoft OneDrive account.

## 🔌 🛠️ Excel Script Connection
Used to access Excel scripts. This connection is separate from *Excel: PowerAutomate Admin Utility* as the scripts may be in a separate Microsoft account.

## 🔌 🛠️ Microsoft Dataverse Connection
General connection to Dataverse. Unlike with file/account-based connectors, everyone working on a project should be able to access all necessary items in the Dataverse, so we use this connection across all solutions. 

## 🔌 🛠️ RegEx Matching (Independent Publisher)
Power Automate does not natively support RegEx. As such, we use independent connectors to perform regular expression operations. This is a general connector used to access RegEx Matching actions. You only need one connection instance to access all actions so this connection can be used across all solutions. 

# Flows

# 🛠️ Copy file as a PDF
Converts a file to PDF format and returns the new content as a data URI. This flow uses the action [Convert file (Preview)](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/connectors/onedrive/#convert-file-(preview)); please see the link to review supported types of files for conversion. In addition to the formats listed, if the file is already a pdf, it does not error but returns the file without modification. 

## Inputs
**File Name *(String)*** – Name of the file to convert. Include the extension.

**File Content URI *(dataURI)*** – File content to convert to PDF

*Note: you can get the data Uri of a file by using the OneDrive action **Get file content** and then using the output file content as an input to the **dataUri** expression: dataUri(outputs('Get_file_content')?['body'])*

## Outputs
**PDF Data URI *(dataURI)*** - File content in pdf format

**Status Code *(Integer)*** - Indicates the status of the flow on termination

 0: Success

-1: Invalid Trigger Inputs

-2: Cannot convert the content of this type.

-3: Temp Files could not be removed

## Dependencies
**Connection References**

🔌 🛠️ PowerAutomate Admin Utility: OneDrive Connection

## Sample

### Sample Inputs
**File Name**

``projects.xlsx``

**File Content URI**

```
data:application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet;base64,
```

### Sample Outputs
**PDF Data URI**

```
data:application/pdf;base64,[](data:application/pdf;base64,)
```

**Status Code**
```
0
```

# 🛠️ Ensure Valid Excel Table

Checks a data URI for an Excel table containing the given columns exists. If the table does not exist, then one is created. No columns are dropped when changing a table, only added if the columns listed do not exist. 

## Inputs

**File Data Uri (string) (optional)** - Contents of the Excel file that need validation. If left empty, the process will use an empty Excel file as a reference (add a table with columns to an empty file). You can create a data Uri by using the *OneDrive [Get file content](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/connectors/onedrive/#get-file-content)* action and then use the *data Uri* expression to turn its output into a data Uri.

**Table Name (string)** - A string representing the table's name.

**Table Columns (String [ ])** - A stringified JSON array of names of columns that the table MUST include in the table. Columns are only added to the table. No columns are removed if they do not exist in the array.

## Outputs

**Excel File (dataUri)** - The dataUri contains the validated Excel content.

**Status Code (Integer)** - The flow status on termination.

 0: Indicates success.

-1: Invalid Trigger: Table Columns

-2: indicates an error: could not create temp reference file.

-3: Cannot Create the Table. The table name may be invalid, or the connection may need to be updated.

-4: Invalid Trigger File Data Uri.

-5: Not all column names can be added. Some strings in the Columns array may be invalid.

-6: Failure in **🛠️ Get Excel Table Columns**

## Dependencies

**Child Flows**

🛠️ Get Excel Table Columns

**Connection References**

🔌 🛠️ PowerAutomate Admin Utility: Excel Connection

🔌 🛠️ PowerAutomate Admin Utility: OneDrive Connection

## Sample

### Sample Inputs

**File Data Uri**
```
data:application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet;base64,
```

**Table Name**
```
CashRecipts
```

**Table Columns**

```json
[
  "Vendor Id",
  "Vendor Name",
  "Date",
  "Invoice Number",
  "Apply Amount",
  "Cheque Number",
   "Chequebook Id",
  "Amount",
  "File",
  "Needs Review"
]
```

### Sample Outputs

**Status Code**

```0```

**Excel File**
```
data:application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet;base64,
```

# 🛠️ Get Excel Table Columns

Gets a stringified JSON array populated with the names of the columns in an Excel Table that has been located with the given inputs.

## Inputs

**File Data Uri (dataUri)** - The file content of the Excel document to analyze.

**Table Name (string)** - A string representing the table's name.

## Outputs

**Table Columns (String [ ])** - A stringified JSON array of names of columns found in the table at the given parameters.

**Status Code (Integer)** – The flow status on termination.

 0: indicates success.

-1: indicates an error: could not create temp reference file.

-2: indicates failure in child flow **🛠️ Get Prop Names**

-3: indicates an error: No Table with Table Name provided.

-4: The table is empty. When the table is empty, we cannot fetch columns.

-5: Indicates an error: invalid dataUri

# 🛠️ Isolate Dollar Amount

Normalizes the input amount. Removes any non-numeric values and ensures the amount has two decimal points. Removes the currency signs:

| Symbol | Name   |
|--------|--------|
| $      | dollar |
| €      | euro   |

## Inputs

******************Amount (string)****************** - A string holding a numerical amount

## Outputs

**Amount *(string)*** - Normalized version of input **Amount.**

# 🛠️ Save Email as PDF

Formats an email into a PDF and saves the resultant PDF file at a given path. The following email fields are formatted in the PDF.

- Recipients
- Sender
- Date Received
- Email Subject
- Email Body
- Number of Attachments

**Note:** We do not include attachments because there is a [limit on the size of the PDF](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/connectors/onedriveforbusiness/) that can be created. To avoid exceeding the size limit, we omit any attachments. If an email contains images in its body, then we send the email content to be processed in Rocket PDF. When images are embedded in the email body, Power Automate does not process this data; thus, you cannot see the images. This is optional; however, if there isn't a Rocket PDF connection, then the email will be processed through Power Automate, and any images in the email will not be visible. 

## Inputs

**Temp Path *(String)*** - The OneDrive folder location where temp file ops will be performed.

**Email *(data URI)*** – The email body returned when using the Power Automate automated flow event [“When a new email arrives”.](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/power-automate/email-triggers) Before passing this value, input it into the data Uri expression: `dataUri(triggerOutputs()?['body'])`.

## Outputs

**Status Code *(integer)*** – Indicates the state of the flow on termination.

 0: Success

-1: Invalid trigger input(s)


**File Content *(data URI)*** – The content of the email. The content will ALWAYS be returned with PDF [mime type](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Basics_of_HTTP/MIME_types/Common_types).

## Dependencies

**Connection References**

🔌 🛠️ PowerAutomate Admin Utility: OneDrive Connection

## Sample
### Sample Inputs
**Temp Path**
`/Temp`

**Email**
```
data:application/json;charset=utf-8;base64,
```
